  "prompt": "Why don't bikes have a gear indicator?",
  "response": "Bike gear indicators, while not ubiquitous, do exist on some models. However, several reasons contribute to why they are not standard on all bikes:\n\n1. **Cost and Complexity**: Adding gear indicators increases manufacturing costs and complexity. For many cyclists, the intuitive feel for gears suffices, so additional indicators are seen as unnecessary.\n\n2. **Weight Concerns**: Cyclists, especially competitive ones, are conscious of weight. Gear indicators add weight, which may be undesirable for those who prioritize a lightweight setup.\n\n3. **Reliability**: Mechanical gear indicators can be prone to malfunction, adding another potential point of failure and maintenance.\n\n4. **Simplicity**: Bicycles are appreciated for their simplicity and efficiency. Adding electronic components like gear indicators can complicate the system, detracting from this simplicity.\n\n5. **User Experience**: Experienced cyclists often develop a feel for their gearing through the tactile feedback from shifting and the effort required to pedal. They may find gear indicators redundant.\n\nHowever, gear indicators can be beneficial for beginners and recreational cyclists, aiding in understanding and optimizing gear use. Some modern bikes, particularly electric bikes and higher-end models, integrate gear indicators into their design to enhance user experience and functionality.",
